      "content": "We can use a technique called \"memoization\" to avoid recalculating the same results multiple times. This can be particularly effective for this problem because of its recursive nature. Here's the updated code:\n\n```python\ndef longest_palindrome(s):\n    memo = {}\n    \n    def expand_around_center(s, left, right):\n        if (left, right) in memo:\n            return memo[(left, right)]\n        if left >= right:\n            return s[left:]\n        \n        if s[left] == s[right]:\n            result = expand_around_center(s, left + 1, right - 1)\n            memo[(left, right)] = result\n            return result\n        else:\n            res1 = expand_around_center(s, left, right - 1)\n            res2 = expand_around_center(s, left + 1, right)\n            res3 = expand_around_center(s, left, right - 1)\n            memo[(left, right)] = max([res1, res2, res3], key=len)\n            return memo[(left, right)]\n    \n    longest = \"\"\n    for i in range(len(s)):\n        res1 = expand_around_center(s, i, i)",
